RESPONSE: <br>
<br>
First, let me school you a bit on responding courteously to someone’s post.  First, attack an argument as aggressively as you want, but never the person making the argument.  In formal debating it’s called an “ad hominem” attack, and it isn’t allowed.   <br>
<br>
My point was that Verant, by the most recent statement THEY made regarding the wizard class, is clearly going to focus more on the wizard’s teleportation abilities than their DD.   My opinion only, but I wouldn’t hold my breath that Verant is going to make any substantive changes to our damage capabilities from here on out.   Sure, they may be tinkered a bit, with but they won’t meaningfully change.   Again it’s just my opinion, but it’s supported by Verant’s recent statement and their past practice.  As to what your “guarntee” is supported by, I confess I’m utterly at a loss. <br>
<br>
Also, you should have been able to figure out that I wasn’t agreeing with Verant’s concentration on teleportation at the expense of DD.  In fact, I believe it’s a ripoff, and I said as much in my post.   HOWEVER, being realistic, I’m trying to put down ideas that work given that’s where THEY (and our class) seem to be heading.  I think working creatively with ports could make us more group-worthy.  Giving us more destinations isn’t going to do anything for us.  Traditional travel ports are sometimes a necessity (to get to certain planes) but are more often a luxury item before, or after, a raid.  I don’t know about you, but I want to have fun in a raid and contribute, not just be a designated driver.   <br>
<br>
Damoen wrote:<br>
<br>
“Teleportation as a weapon makes no sense to me. The idea of porting a mob to your location. Has so many problems with it. This spell would have such aggro on it that it would be pure suicide to cast. Higher level (i.e post 50) mobs can gate. And this spell would aggro those mobs surrounding the mob after it gated upon casting. Bringing all those mobs onto the wizard. The idea of setting a teleport location to port the mobs to still does not take into account aggro. &quot;Letting the wizard scout for a bit.&quot; A wizard is not designed to scout. If this spell is cast at one mob surrounded by two other mobs you will aggro those other mobs also.”<br>
<br>
RESPONSE:<br>
<br>
You say it makes no sense but then go on to talk about aggro.  Aggro is coded.  Verant has, and could, reprogram aggro (witness a few patches ago they tinkered with chanter and cleric aggro).  Also, as you point out, many times MOBs “gate” back to their spawns.  Sometimes this is not by design but just through weak coding (e.g., level 40’s spirocs in Timorous Deep, when severely wounded, will “gate” back to their spawn points).  Theoretically these MOBs are about as aggro as they can be when they gate, it’s just that they lack the health to do anything about it.  They do not aggro nearby full HP MOBs, however, and there is no reason to assume this couldn’t be programmed into the spells I suggest. <br>
<br>
As for your assertion that a “wizard is not designed to scout”, I heartily disagree.  With our sight spells and powers of invisibility, we make excellent scouts.  I have often scouted an area for my party.  This is not to say a wizard needs to pull, but I don’t think the idea of porting MOBs is inherently “un”-wizard.   Someone else suggested Call of The Hero is a summoning spell.  Whatever.  You could make the argument that our ports are summons of a kind, and an Eye of Zom is a summoning as well.  I don’t think we need to get hung up on the semantics of a fantasy game world.  Point one is “can it be programmed?”  Point two is “would it be more fun for wizards?”   I say “should be” and “would be.”<br>
